ToroidZip
=========

A ratio-first compression codec for smooth floating-point data.

Encodes float64 sequences as ratios (x[n] / x[n-1]) rather than absolute
values. Ratio distributions in smooth data are tightly clustered around 1.0
(the Identity state), yielding a better entropy model than value-based codecs.
Boundary events (near-zero or extreme ratios) are handled as a separate class
rather than disrupting the main distribution.

Theoretical basis: Toroidal Arithmetic — a ratio-first number system where 0
and ∞ are boundary poles rather than algebraic values, and identity (x/x=1)
is treated as a higher-order law than value equality.

Status: Milestone 15 complete — analyzer correctness (AnalyzeTiersV8: u8/u16/u24/u32/f64
routing mirrors v8 encoder exactly, no 16-bit cap); Milestone 14 complete (writeup
Sections 1–7, Library API); 195 passing tests, 80%+ coverage.

Usage
-----

  go install github.com/Destraag/toroidzip/cmd/toroidzip@latest

  # Lossless encode/decode (rANS entropy coding)
  toroidzip encode input.f64 output.tzrz
  toroidzip decode input.tzrz output.f64

  # Lossy encode with end-to-end 4 significant figure guarantee
  toroidzip encode -n 4 input.f64 output.tzrz
  toroidzip encode --sig-figs 4 input.f64 output.tzrz   # same

  # Lossy encode by storage byte width (1=u8/~2sf, 2=u16/~4sf, 3=u24/~7sf, 4=u32/~9sf)
  toroidzip encode --bytes 2 input.f64 output.tzrz

  # Auto-select entropy mode from data (lossless if compressible, else advise)
  toroidzip encode --auto input.f64 output.tzrz
  toroidzip encode -a input.f64 output.tzrz              # same

  # Auto-select with lossy adaptive encoding
  toroidzip encode -a --lossy input.f64 output.tzrz

  # Analyze data before encoding (precision, drift, lossless viability, tier preview)
  toroidzip analyze input.f64

  # Adaptive tier preview — show % u16 / u32 / float64 at a given tolerance
  toroidzip analyze -n 6 input.f64
  toroidzip analyze --tolerance 1e-6 input.f64

Input/output: raw IEEE 754 little-endian float64 binary files.

Flags (encode)
--------------

  --entropy-mode raw|lossless|quantized|adaptive
      raw:       no entropy coding (stream v1, baseline)
      lossless:  rANS-coded ratio stream (stream v2, default)
      quantized: lossy N-bit log-space quantization (stream v3)
      adaptive:  per-ratio tiered hybrid — u8 / u16 / u24 / u32 / float64 (stream v8)
                 tier chosen by offset magnitude; PrecisionBits controls quantization grid

  --sig-figs N, -n N
      Guarantee N significant decimal figures in reconstructed values, end-to-end.
      This is the recommended lossy flag for most users.
      Internally sets PrecisionBits=SigFigsToBits(N+2), enables adaptive reanchoring,
      and caps reanchor interval at 10,000 as a circuit-breaker backstop
      (the adaptive drift check is the real guarantee; K_max is last resort).
      Prints the selected storage tier to stderr on encode.
      Cannot be combined with --auto, --bytes, --precision, or a non-adaptive --entropy-mode.
      Power users may override the derived per-ratio ε with an explicit --tolerance.

  --bytes 1|2|3|4
      Select storage tier by byte width: 1=u8 (~2 sig figs), 2=u16 (~4 sig figs),
      3=u24 (~7 sig figs), 4=u32 (~9 sig figs). Implies adaptive mode. PrecisionBits=B controls the
      quantization grid; periodic reanchor (default interval 256) handles drift.
      No end-to-end accuracy guarantee — use --sig-figs for that.
      Prints the selected tier to stderr on encode.
      Cannot be combined with --sig-figs, --bytes, --precision, or --auto.

  --tolerance T
      Max relative error per ratio in adaptive mode (e.g. 1e-4).
      When set alongside --sig-figs, overrides the auto-derived per-ratio ε
      (T_end guarantee is still enforced by adaptive reanchoring).
      Cannot be used without --entropy-mode adaptive (except alongside --sig-figs).

  --precision N
      Precision bits for quantized or adaptive mode (1–30).
      In adaptive mode, controls quantization grid and u8/u16/u24/u32 tier routing.
      Cannot be combined with --sig-figs.

  --auto, -a
      Auto-select entropy mode by analyzing the input.
      Cannot be combined with --sig-figs.

  --lossy
      With --auto: use adaptive encoding at recommended precision and ε=1e-4.
      Requires --auto.

  --drift-mode A|B|C
      A = periodic reanchor, original values as anchors (default; fastest)
      B = Kahan compensate; encoder tracks decoder's accumulated product exactly
      C = quantize; encoder mirrors decoder's float32-rounded accumulation

  --reanchor-interval N
      Safety cap on verbatim anchor cadence (default 256; default 10,000 with --sig-figs).
      Adaptive reanchoring may fire earlier when --sig-figs is active.
      An explicit value here overrides the --sig-figs derived cap.

Flags (analyze)
---------------

  --sig-figs N, -n N   show adaptive tier preview for N sig figs
  --bytes 1|2|3|4      show adaptive tier preview for this byte width
  --tolerance T        show adaptive tier preview at this ε
  --precision N        u16 precision bits for tier preview (default: recommended bits)

Library API
-----------

  The codec package is importable directly. The CLI is a thin wrapper around it.

  import "github.com/Destraag/toroidzip/codec"

  Encode:

    err := codec.Encode(values, w, codec.EncodeOptions{
        EntropyMode:   codec.EntropyAdaptive,
        PrecisionBits: codec.SigFigsToBits(5),       // 5 sig figs → B=16
        Tolerance:     math.MaxFloat64,               // fast path: quantize all normals
        AdaptiveReanchor:   true,
        EndToEndTolerance:  codec.SigFigsToTolerance(5), // ε = 5e-5
        ReanchorInterval:   codec.SigFigsToMaxK(5),      // circuit-breaker cap
    })

  Decode:

    values, err := codec.Decode(r)

  Decode reads the version byte from the stream and dispatches automatically.
  No options are required.

  Key EncodeOptions fields:

    EntropyMode       EntropyRaw | EntropyLossless | EntropyQuantized | EntropyAdaptive
                      EntropyAdaptive (stream v8) is the recommended lossy mode.
                      EntropyLossless (stream v2) is the recommended lossless mode.

    PrecisionBits     Log-space quantisation depth (1–30).
                      Use codec.SigFigsToBits(N) to derive from a sig-figs target.
                      Example: SigFigsToBits(5) = 16.

    Tolerance         Fast-path gate. Set math.MaxFloat64 when using SigFigsToBits
                      as the accuracy driver (recommended). Set SigFigsToTolerance(N)
                      for per-ratio error gating (activates ClassNormalExact fallback).

    AdaptiveReanchor  When true, the encoder fires a verbatim reanchor whenever the
                      accumulated reconstruction error approaches EndToEndTolerance.
                      This is the mechanism that makes the end-to-end guarantee hold.

    EndToEndTolerance Maximum relative reconstruction error guaranteed for every
                      decoded value. Set codec.SigFigsToTolerance(N) = 0.5×10^-N.

    DriftMode         DriftReanchor (A, default, fastest) | DriftCompensate (B) |
                      DriftQuantize (C, mirrors float32 decoder accumulation).
                      DriftCompensate uses Kahan log-space accumulation; ~3.4× slower
                      but strictly more accurate at the same reanchor interval.
                      DriftQuantize (C) is retained for compatibility; --auto never
                      recommends it.

    ReanchorInterval  Safety cap on reanchor cadence. With AdaptiveReanchor=true this
                      is a maximum: reanchors may fire earlier. Default 256; use
                      SigFigsToMaxK(N) (= 10,000) when AdaptiveReanchor is active.

  Convenience helpers:

    codec.SigFigsToBits(N int) int         B = ceil(log₂(8 / log₂(1 + 5×10^-N)))
    codec.SigFigsToTolerance(N int) float64  ε = 0.5 × 10^-N
    codec.SigFigsToMaxK(N int) int         circuit-breaker cap (returns 10,000)
    codec.BitsToSigFigs(B int) int         inverse: bits → sig figs

  Minimal lossless embed example:

    func readTZRZ(path string) ([]float64, error) {
        f, err := os.Open(path)
        if err != nil {
            return nil, err
        }
        defer f.Close()
        return codec.Decode(f)
    }

  Minimal lossy encode example (5 sig figs, end-to-end guarantee):

    func writeTZRZ(values []float64, path string) error {
        f, err := os.Create(path)
        if err != nil {
            return err
        }
        defer f.Close()
        N := 5
        return codec.Encode(values, f, codec.EncodeOptions{
            EntropyMode:       codec.EntropyAdaptive,
            PrecisionBits:     codec.SigFigsToBits(N),
            Tolerance:         math.MaxFloat64,
            AdaptiveReanchor:  true,
            EndToEndTolerance: codec.SigFigsToTolerance(N),
            ReanchorInterval:  codec.SigFigsToMaxK(N),
        })
    }

Structure
---------

  codec/          encode/decode logic, boundary classification, rANS, quantization
  codec/analyze.go  AnalyzeDrift, AnalyzePrecision, ExtractNormalRatios, AnalyzeTiers
  cmd/toroidzip/  CLI binary (encode, decode, analyze subcommands)
  scripts/        bench_m4.sh — external baseline benchmark vs zstd/brotli/fpzip
                    usage: ./scripts/bench_m4.sh [--n N] [--effort fast|best|both]
                                                  [--sig-figs N] [--adaptive] [--keep]
                  gen_datasets/ — synthetic .f64 dataset generator
  PLAN            algorithm design and session log
  ROADMAP         milestone tracker

